\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
NUCL 511 HMWK 3
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Alex Hagen
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
2/5/14
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Consider a three-group representation of a thermal reactor spectrum composed
 of a fission spectrum, a 
\begin_inset Formula $1/E$
\end_inset

 spectrum, and a Maxwell spectrum
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{1}(E)=A_{1}\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\frac{\sqrt{E}}{\left(kT_{1}\right)^{3/2}}e^{-E/kT_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
with 
\begin_inset Formula $kT_{1}=1.4\, MeV$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}=820.3\, keV<E<E_{0}=20\, MeV$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{2}(E)=\frac{A_{2}}{E}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{2}=0.1\, eV<E\leq E_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(E)dE=A_{3}\frac{E}{(kT_{3})^{2}}e^{-E/kT_{3}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
with 
\begin_inset Formula $kT_{3}=0.0253\, eV$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{3}=0\leq E\leq E_{2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subparagraph*
Find the normalization constants 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

 such that the spectrum is continuous at the group boundaries and the integratio
n over the whole energy range is unity.
 Evaluate the group-wise integrals numerically if necessary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have one integral equation with three boundary conditions for this problem.
 To ensure the integration over the whole energy range is unity, we must
 have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{E_{0}}\varphi(E)dE=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Which, because the spectrum is discrete, becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{E_{3}}^{E_{2}}\varphi_{3}(E)dE+\int_{E_{2}}^{E_{1}}\varphi_{2}(E)dE+\int_{E_{1}}^{E_{0}}\varphi_{1}(E)dE=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{0.1\, eV}A_{3}\frac{E}{(kT_{3})^{2}}e^{-E/kT_{3}}dE+\int_{0.1\, eV}^{820.3\, keV}\frac{A_{2}}{E}dE+\int_{820.3\, keV}^{20\, MeV}A_{1}\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\frac{\sqrt{E}}{\left(kT_{1}\right)^{3/2}}e^{-E/kT_{1}}dE=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To integrate the first term, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varphi_{3}$
\end_inset

, we can use integration by parts
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{A_{3}}{\left(kT_{3}\right)^{2}}\int_{E_{3}}^{E_{2}}Ee^{-E/kT_{3}}dE
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u=E,\; v=?
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
du=?,\; dv=e^{-E/kT_{3}}dE
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and we find that 
\begin_inset Formula $du=dE$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v=-kT_{3}e^{-E/kT_{3}}$
\end_inset

, so
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int udv=uv-\int vdu
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int Ee^{-E/kT_{3}}=-EkT_{3}e^{-E/kT_{3}}-\int-kT_{3}e^{-E/kT_{3}}dE=kT_{3}Ee^{-E/kT_{3}}+kT_{3}\int e^{-E/kT_{3}}dE=kT_{3}Ee^{-E/kT_{3}}-\left(kT_{3}\right)^{2}e^{-E/kT_{3}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
so the integral is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{A_{3}}{\left(kT_{3}\right)^{2}}\left[kT_{3}Ee^{-E/kT_{3}}-\left(kT_{3}\right)^{2}e^{-E/kT_{3}}\right]_{E_{3}}^{E_{2}}=
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second integral is simply done, and is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A_{2}\left[\ln(E)\right]_{E_{2}}^{E_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And finally, the third integration is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{A_{1}}{\left(kT_{1}\right)^{3/2}}\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\int_{E_{1}}^{E_{0}}\sqrt{E}e^{-E/kT_{1}}dE=\{\}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The numerical integration included in MATLAB's Symbolic Toolbox was used,
 which utilizes an adaptive Simpson quadrature method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mathworks2013"

\end_inset

.
 This method estimates the integral as a series of trapezoids under the
 curve (called Simpon's Rule), but also calculates the derivative of the
 function, and increases the amount of trapezoids used in quickly varying
 regions of the function 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 458, 505-506"
key "Bradie2006"

\end_inset

.
 We can determine the integral equation to be equivalent to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(9.173\times10^{-10}\right)A_{1}+\left(15.920\right)A_{2}+\left(0.905\right)A_{3}=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We also have the continuity conditions, such that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{3}(E_{2})=\varphi_{2}(E_{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.A_{3}\frac{E}{(kT_{3})^{2}}e^{-E/kT_{3}}\right|_{E_{2}}=\left.\frac{A_{2}}{E}\right|_{E_{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(3.000\right)A_{3}=\left(10.0\right)A_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi_{2}(E_{1})=\varphi_{1}(E_{1})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left.A_{1}\frac{2}{\sqrt{\pi}}\frac{\sqrt{E}}{\left(kT_{1}\right)^{3/2}}e^{-E/kT_{1}}\right|_{E_{1}}=\left.\frac{A_{2}}{E}\right|_{E_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(4.146\times10^{-16}\right)A_{1}=\left(1.21\times10^{-6}\right)A_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These three equations help us solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Reiterating
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(9.173\times10^{-10}\right)A_{1}+\left(15.920\right)A_{2}+\left(0.905\right)A_{3}=1
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(3.000\right)A_{3}=\left(10.0\right)A_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(4.146\times10^{-16}\right)A_{1}=\left(1.21\times10^{-6}\right)A_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
9.173\times10^{-10} & 15.920 & 0.905\\
0 & 10 & -3\\
4.146\times10^{-16} & -1.21\times10^{-6} & 0
\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
A_{1}\\
A_{2}\\
A_{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
which can be solved any number of ways, including backdivision.
 Again, MATLAB's symbolic Toolbox allows us to solve this without explicitly
 writing a numerical method.
 The toolbox uses Cholesky Factorization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Mathworks2013"

\end_inset

 to invert the matrix and multiply that by the solution vector.
 The Cholesky factorization decomposes the matrix into a lower triangular
 matrix and is more efficient than LU decomposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after "p. 216"
key "Bradie2006"

\end_inset

.
 This gives the constants
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
A_{1}\\
A_{2}\\
A_{3}
\end{array}\right]=\left[\begin{array}{c}
0.1641\\
0.04623\\
0.1541
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these constants, we can plot the spectrum, as shown in Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Energy Spectrum given by varphi1, varphi2, and varphi3"

\end_inset

.
 This spectrum shows the typical shape of a fission spectrum, with a fast
 and thermal hump, and also demonstrates the continuity of the solution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

